Independent presidential candidate Joe Nyagah has called on Uhuru Kenyatta to intervene in the Middle East dispute pitying Qatar against other countries.He warned on Sunday that the dispute with Saudi Arabia, Bahrain, Egypt and the United Arab Emirates will be disastrous if left unattended.The countries severed relations with Qatar on Monday, accusing it of supporting Islamist militants and their adversary Iran - allegations Qatar says are baseless. Several countries followed suit.Qatari nationals have been served with an official two-week notice to leave neighbouring countries as diplomatic sanctions deepen.Those countries also banned their citizens from entering Qatar.More on this: Qatar row: Four countries cut links with Qatar, UAE gives diplomats 48hrs to leaveAlso read: Qatari planes banned from Egyptian and Saudi air spaceNyagah, who was Uhuru's adviser on regional matters until May, noted Kenya has over the years been instrumental in reconciling warring countries.He said the country should step into the Qatar case and help resolve the dispute quickly and amicably.&ldquo;I call upon our country to help reconcile our friends in the Middle East in order to ensure our brothers...resolve their differences,&rdquo; he said in a statement.&ldquo;Kenya has over the years been involved in helping reconcile groups and countries in conflicts within our region and beyond. This is a contribution the world has come to know us for."Nyagah resigned to vie against President Uhuru Kenyatta and Deputy President William Ruto in the August 8 general election.Read: Uhuru, Raila and Dida among 8 presidential nominees on IEBC shortlist